senses.sense: (transitive) To encourage or sanction (something).
(transitive) To experience or suffer (an injury, etc.).
examples: The building sustained major damage in the earthquake.

senses.sense: (transitive) To confirm, prove, or corroborate; to uphold.
examples: to sustain a charge, an accusation, or a proposition

senses.sense: (law, of a judge) To allow, accept, or admit (e.g. an objection or motion) as valid.
To keep from falling; to bear; to uphold; to support.
examples: A foundation sustains the superstructure; an animal sustains a load; a rope sustains a weight.

senses.sense: To aid, comfort, or relieve; to vindicate.
(music) A mechanism which can be used to hold a note, as the right pedal on a piano.
Able to be sustained.
Able to be produced or sustained for an indefinite period without damaging the environment, or without depleting a resource; renewable.
examples: sustainable economy

senses.sense: A renewable energy source.
